In Kenya, there has not been a total lockdown in any county and none is expected before January. The teachers and students are, therefore, likely to transmit infections to schools on January 4, arising from their end-of-year social interactions. This will happen in a state in which schools are congested and social distancing overlooked.
 Not all is lost, however. Reports from various countries, including the USA, Russia, the United Kingdom and India, are that they have developed vaccines. In view of this development, it is my view that the government should move with speed to purchase these vaccines and prioritise vaccination of teachers and students as well as medical personnel to counter the effects of congestion and overlooking social distancing. However, the logistics of procuring and carrying out vaccination will take time.
As a compromise between the importance of the safety of the students and the need for them to be in school, could the government consider reopening of Standard Six, Standard Seven in primary, and Form Three in secondary in January, alongside Grade Four, Standard Eight and Form Four as vaccinations get underway? The student population at both levels will be 50 per cent.



